 shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Coucy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Arabic   Khoury   or   Khouri   ‘priest’. Compare   Courey  ,   Couri  , and   Cury  .","French: habitational name from a place so named in Vienne."],"variants":[{"name":"Khoury","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Nabil, Sami, Samir, Issa, Ibrahim, Ramzi, Bassam, Fouad, Habib, Issam, Jamil, Riad.  French Michel, Antoine, Emile, Pierre, Andre, Camille, Clemence, Clovis, Georges, Gisele, Henri, Jacques.","Arabic (mainly Lebanon, Syria, and Jordan): from <i>khūrī</i> ‘priest’, in particular a Christian priest. This surname is used among Christians, including Assyrians/Chaldeans. Compare   Cory  ,   Coury  ,   Cury  ,   Elkhoury  ,   Khouri  ,   Kory  ,   Koury  , and   Kury  ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Enguerrand II de Coucy was born about 1155 as the son of Robert I de Coucy and Beatrix de Saint Pol. He married Adèle de Nesle. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1224, at the age of 70."},"et":{"about 1155–1224":"umbes 1155–1224","1155–1224":"1155–1224","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1166–1215":"1166–1215","1168–1244":"1168–1244","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1196–1257":"1196–1257","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1109–1191":"1109–1191","–1192":"–1192","26 July 1191":"26. juuli 1191","1263":"1263","1175":"1175","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1192":"1192","1191":"1191","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1168":"1168","1244":"1244","1166":"1166","1155":"1155","about 1155":"umbes 1155","1109":"1109","Boves, Somme, Picardie, France":"Boves, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Acre, Palestine":"Acre, Northern, Palestiina","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Laon, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1155–1224":"noin 1155–1224","1155–1224":"1155–1224","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1166–1215":"1166–1215","1168–1244":"1168–1244","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1196–1257":"1196–1257","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1109–1191":"1109–1191","–1192":"–1192","26 July 1191":"26. heinäkuuta 1191","1263":"1263","1175":"1175","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1192":"1192","1191":"1191","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1168":"1168","1244":"1244","1166":"1166","1155":"1155","about 1155":"noin 1155","1109":"1109","Boves, Somme, Picardie, France":"Boves, Somme, Picardie, Ranska","Acre, Palestine":"Acre, Northern, Palestiina","Coucy-le-Château-Au